john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1669,"month":11,"day":16,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1741,"month":10,"day":11,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"T00035","mother_id":"U00012"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 45"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"U00022","children_ids":["T00065","T00066","T00067","X00436"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1705,"date_year":1693},{"spouse_id":"U00017","children_ids":["T00068","I00054","T00070","T00071","T00072","T00073","X00446"],"marriage_number":2,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1738}],"political_offices":[{"title":"Governor","jurisdiction":"Colony of Connecticut","dates":"1724-1741","duration_years":17,"notes":"First Governor of Connecticut born within its limits. Longest-serving after Gov. Winthrop. Died in office Oct 11, 1741."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"H00115","display_label":"Son-in-law signed his estate — 'Nathaniel Hooker and Eunice Hooker'","link_text":"Captain Nathaniel Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00360","display_label":"His granddaughter Esther married Rev. Noadiah Russell in 1758","link_text":"Noadiah Russell"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"U00020","display_label":"was the Deputy Governor whose death opened his path","link_text":"Nathan Gold"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics"],"notable_blurb":"First Connecticut governor born within its limits","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"First Connecticut governor born within the colony","body":"Born in Hartford on November 16, 1669, Joseph Talcott was the first Governor of Connecticut born within the colony rather than in England. He served from 1724 until his death on October 11, 1741 — 17 years in office, longer than any predecessor except Governor Winthrop and any successor until the modern era. His funeral expenses of £69 12s. 6d. were paid from the Colonial Treasury.","number":1,"category":"politics"},{"header":"He presided in the upper house the afternoon","body":"When his wife Eunice died suddenly about noon on Thursday, May 25, 1738, the Deputy Governor was absent at Norwich. Governor Talcott did not let his private grief interfere with his official duty — he returned and presided in the upper house that same afternoon. The General Assembly appointed a committee to draw an address of condolence to the Governor.","number":2,"category":"politics"},{"header":"His estate was signed by 'Nathaniel Hooker","body":"At the Court of Probate, Hartford, on December 25, 1742, the distribution of Governor Talcott's estate was signed by all children as co-heirs. Among the signatures: 'Nathaniel Hooker and Eunice Hooker' — his daughter Eunice Talcott and her husband Nathaniel Hooker 2d. The Talcott-Hooker convergence was entered into the public record.","number":3,"category":"family"},{"header":"Three of his children each found a separate","body":"His daughter Eunice married Nathaniel Hooker 2d — direct Hooker surname. His son Matthew married Mary Russell, a Hooker descendant through the Pierpont branch. His daughter Abigail married Rev. Daniel Wadsworth; their son Jeremiah later married Mary's own sister Mehitable Russell, also a Hooker descendant.","number":4,"category":"family"},{"header":"Petitioned for his father's estate by primogeniture","body":"Joseph Talcott was the fourth son of Lt.-Col. John Talcott Jr. but the eldest to survive his father. In 1691, at age 21, he petitioned the General Court for his father's estate by right of primogeniture — an assertive legal claim for colonial Connecticut. He was first mentioned in public life in 1711 as a committee member to lay out the town of Coventry.","number":5,"category":"law"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Go